							<td>Nation</td>
							<td>nazione</td>
							<td>natsija</td>
							<td>nación</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>studiar</td>
							<td>study</td>
							<td>étudier</td>
							<td>studieren</td>
							<td>studiare</td>
							<td>izuchat</td>
							<td>estudiar</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td>yuna</td>
							<td>young</td>
							<td>jeune</td>
							<td>jung</td>
							<td>giovane</td>
							<td>yunyi, molodoy</td>
							<td>joven</td>
						</tr>
					</tbody>
				</table>
				<p>Ido decided to continoue without <i>t</i> (as in Esperanto), but to drop the French <i>i</i> (or <i>j</i> in Esperanto). In Ido: <i>semano</i>, compare: <i>semanjo</i><br>This happens everywhere in Esperanto, since Esperantos philosophy is different. But this doesnt make Ido less bias towards French, or anyother language for that matter!<br>The Esperanto word for <i>dirt, mire</i> is <i>koto</i>, taken from German <i>Kot</i>. Problem here, is that the German word <i>Kot</i> has lost it's meaning for <i>dirt, mire</i>, and today only mean slang for <i>crap, shit etc</i>. Ido takes a look at French, Spanish and Italians word for <i>dirt, mire</i>: <i>fange</i>, <i>fango</i> and <i>fango</i>, and decided to take <i>fango</i>.<br>Even though Esperanto at time are bias towards French and German, and Ido correcting it, doent mean Ido are the opposite, neglecting them! Ido, for example, takes the French imperative <i>-ez</i>, oppose to Esperanto <i>-u</i>, and French ordinal <i>-ième</i> (in the form of <i>-esma</i>), oppose to Esperanto <i>-a</i>, and on the German side takes the German word for chicken/rooster <i>Huhn or Hahn</i>, and endup with <i>hano</i> (neutral, <i>rooster - hanulo, chicken - hanino</i>), oppose to Esperanto <i>koko</i> (male, <i>female - kokino</i>), and takes the German word for yeast <i>Hefe</i>, and endup with <i>hefo</i>, again, oppose to Esperanto <i>gisto</i>. Ido takes words in a smart and effective way, if none of the languages are united (or the majority), than Ido looks elsewhere!</p>
				<p>Idos philosophy is: <u> to be as easy of a language as possible for the most amount of peaople as possible</u>, so that the most amount of people will have it easeier to learn (a universal second language); that is why the Delegation chose 6 specific languages as "control languages", or as we call them in Ido "the front languages (la fronta lingui)", they are: English (ca. 1.5 billion speakers), French (ca. 220 million speakers), German (ca. 100 million speakers), Italian (ca. 60 million speakers), Russian (165 million speakers), Spanish (490 million speakers). They are the most spoken languages in the world that have alot of things in common. Sadly, any Arabic, Chinese, etc. words where not introduced in Ido; they are a bit too different, and they would drag down the other languages. But, in return, by not selecting other languages, they got the following chart:</p>
				<div class="ui green active progress" data-percent="38">
					<div class="bar" style="transition: 300ms; -webkit-transition: 300ms; width: 38%;">
						<div class="progress">38%</div>
